{
  "nextId": 53,
  "root": {
    "id": 0,
    "text": "A train car is freely coasting around a large circular track. It is then switched to a smaller circular track. How does its speed change? Assume no friction.<br><br><img src='images/switch.png'/>",
    "debater": "questioner",
    "level": 0,
    "parentId": null,
    "honest_response": "",
    "dishonest_response": "",
    "children": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "text": "The speed stays the same when we model the car as a <a xdef=\"point_mass\">point mass</a>. It decreases slightly when modeled as a <a xdef=\"rigid_body\">rigid body</a>.",
        "debater": "honest",
        "level": 1,
        "parentId": 0,
        "honest_response": "Yes",
        "dishonest_response": "No",
        "children": [
          {
            "id": 3,
            "text": "A ball on a string spins faster when its radius is reduced, and the same principle applies as the car transitions to a tighter radius.",
            "debater": "dishonest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 1,
            "honest_response": "No",
            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
            "children": [
              {
                "id": 9,
                "text": "The string does work because, as the ball spirals inward, its velocity has a radial component aligned with the tension.",
                "debater": "honest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 3,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": []
              },
              {
                "id": 10,
                "text": "The fixed frictionless track exerts only a normal constraint force perpendicular to the car's velocity, so unlike the string it does no work.",
                "debater": "honest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 3,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "No",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "id": 12,
                    "text": "Curvature changes continuously along the connecting arc, causing the direction of the constraint force to rotate.",
                    "debater": "dishonest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 10,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": []
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 13,
                    "text": "This rotation means the force cannot remain perfectly perpendicular to velocity.",
                    "debater": "dishonest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 10,
                    "honest_response": "No",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "id": 15,
                        "text": "The car's velocity is <a xdef=\"tangent\">tangent</a> to the track at every point. The constraint force is <a xdef=\"normal\">normal</a> to the track, hence perpendicular to velocity.",
                        "debater": "honest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 13,
                        "honest_response": "Yes",
                        "dishonest_response": "No",
                        "children": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 16,
                        "text": "At every instant, the force and velocity rotate together. Perpendicularity is maintained even as curvature changes.",
                        "debater": "honest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 13,
                        "honest_response": "Yes",
                        "dishonest_response": "No",
                        "children": [
                          {
                            "id": 18,
                            "text": "On a changing-curvature path, the constraint force must adjust in both magnitude and direction.",
                            "debater": "dishonest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 16,
                            "honest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                            "children": []
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 19,
                            "text": "The centripetal acceleration behaves differently on the connecting track than it does on either circular section.",
                            "debater": "dishonest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 16,
                            "honest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                            "children": []
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 41,
                            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [16].",
                            "debater": "dishonest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 16,
                            "honest_response": "No",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                            "children": [
                              {
                                "id": 33,
                                "text": "The force adjusts direction to maintain perpendicularity; it rotates to stay normal as velocity rotates to stay tangent.",
                                "debater": "honest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 41,
                                "honest_response": "Yes",
                                "dishonest_response": "No",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 34,
                                "text": "Centripetal force remains perpendicular to the velocity throughout, regardless of how its magnitude varies.",
                                "debater": "honest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 41,
                                "honest_response": "Yes",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 42,
                                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [None].",
                                "debater": "honest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 41,
                                "honest_response": "Yes",
                                "dishonest_response": "No",
                                "children": []
                              }
                            ]
                          }
                        ]
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 43,
                        "text": "Therefore, you should reject [13].",
                        "debater": "honest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 13,
                        "honest_response": "Yes",
                        "dishonest_response": "",
                        "children": []
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 44,
                    "text": "Therefore, you should reject [10].",
                    "debater": "dishonest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 10,
                    "honest_response": "",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": []
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": 45,
                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [3].",
                "debater": "honest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 3,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "",
                "children": []
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "id": 4,
            "text": "The connecting track provides a <a xdef=\"radially\">radially</a> inward force that accelerates the car <a xdef=\"tangentially\">tangentially</a>.",
            "debater": "dishonest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 1,
            "honest_response": "No",
            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "id": 46,
            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [1].",
            "debater": "dishonest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 1,
            "honest_response": "",
            "dishonest_response": "Yes",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": 2,
        "text": "The speed increases if we model the car as a <a xdef=\"point_mass\">point mass</a>. It also increases if we model it as a <a xdef=\"rigid_body\">rigid body</a>.",
        "debater": "dishonest",
        "level": 1,
        "parentId": 0,
        "honest_response": "No",
        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
        "children": [
          {
            "id": 6,
            "text": "On a frictionless track, the rails' <a xdef=\"constraint_force\">constraint force</a> does no work, so <a xdef=\"ke\">kinetic energy (KE)</a> is conserved and speed cannot increase.",
            "debater": "honest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 2,
            "honest_response": "Yes",
            "dishonest_response": "No",
            "children": [
              {
                "id": 24,
                "text": "If the rails truly do no work, a point-mass car will not lose speed on the smaller track.",
                "debater": "dishonest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 6,
                "honest_response": "Yes",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": []
              },
              {
                "id": 25,
                "text": "Yet if kinetic energy is conserved while the rails do no work, a rigid body on a frictionless track does not slow down, contradicting [1].",
                "debater": "dishonest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 6,
                "honest_response": "No",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "id": 27,
                    "text": "A rigid body has translational and rotational kinetic energy; a point mass has only translational.",
                    "debater": "honest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 25,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                    "children": []
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 28,
                    "text": "On a tighter track, rotational kinetic energy increases at the expense of translational kinetic energy.",
                    "debater": "honest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 25,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "No",
                    "children": [
                      {
                        "id": 30,
                        "text": "This holds only when the body is mechanically constrained to yaw with the track curvature (rigid link between axles and body), which has not been established.",
                        "debater": "dishonest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 28,
                        "honest_response": "No",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                        "children": [
                          {
                            "id": 36,
                            "text": "Both axles are constrained to the rails, so the body's orientation is pinned by the chord between the two axle positions.",
                            "debater": "honest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 30,
                            "honest_response": "Yes",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                            "children": []
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 37,
                            "text": "On a curved section, this geometry causes the body to yaw as it advances.",
                            "debater": "honest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 30,
                            "honest_response": "Yes",
                            "dishonest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                            "children": []
                          },
                          {
                            "id": 47,
                            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [30].",
                            "debater": "honest",
                            "level": 6,
                            "parentId": 30,
                            "honest_response": "Yes",
                            "dishonest_response": "No",
                            "children": [
                              {
                                "id": 39,
                                "text": "A car whose axles are rigidly fixed parallel to its body cannot roll without slipping on a curved track.",
                                "debater": "dishonest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 47,
                                "honest_response": "Yes but omits key info",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 40,
                                "text": "The curvature differs at the front and rear contact points on the connecting track, with consequences for yaw and speed.",
                                "debater": "dishonest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 47,
                                "honest_response": "No",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                                "children": []
                              },
                              {
                                "id": 48,
                                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [None].",
                                "debater": "dishonest",
                                "level": 7,
                                "parentId": 47,
                                "honest_response": "No",
                                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                                "children": []
                              }
                            ]
                          }
                        ]
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 31,
                        "text": "Without that constraint, total KE stays translational and the speed does not fall.",
                        "debater": "dishonest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 28,
                        "honest_response": "No",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                        "children": []
                      },
                      {
                        "id": 49,
                        "text": "Therefore, you should reject [28].",
                        "debater": "dishonest",
                        "level": 5,
                        "parentId": 28,
                        "honest_response": "",
                        "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                        "children": []
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "id": 50,
                    "text": "Therefore, you should reject [25].",
                    "debater": "honest",
                    "level": 4,
                    "parentId": 25,
                    "honest_response": "Yes",
                    "dishonest_response": "",
                    "children": []
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "id": 51,
                "text": "Therefore, you should reject [6].",
                "debater": "dishonest",
                "level": 3,
                "parentId": 6,
                "honest_response": "",
                "dishonest_response": "Yes",
                "children": []
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "id": 7,
            "text": "There is simply nothing on a fixed frictionless track that can add energy to the car.",
            "debater": "honest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 2,
            "honest_response": "Yes",
            "dishonest_response": "No",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "id": 52,
            "text": "Therefore, you should reject [2].",
            "debater": "honest",
            "level": 2,
            "parentId": 2,
            "honest_response": "Yes",
            "dishonest_response": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "defs_and_sources": "<defs>\n  <def id=\"point_mass\">Point mass - An idealized object with mass but no spatial extent, used to simplify analysis by ignoring rotation and internal structure.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"rigid_body\">Rigid body - An idealized solid object in which the distance between every pair of points remains constant, so it can rotate as well as translate.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"tangent\">Tangent - A straight line that touches a curve at exactly one point and points in the direction the curve is heading at that point.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"radially\">Radially - In the direction pointing toward or away from the center of a circular path.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"tangentially\">Tangentially - In the direction along the instantaneous velocity of an object moving on a curved path, i.e. perpendicular to the radial direction.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"normal\">Normal - Perpendicular to a surface or line at a given point.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"constraint_force\">Constraint force - A force exerted by a surface, track, or other boundary that restricts an object's motion to a particular path.</def>\n\n  <def id=\"ke\">Kinetic energy (KE) - The energy an object possesses due to its motion, equal to ½mv² for an object of mass m moving at speed v.</def>\n</defs>"
}
